Operating Procedures:  The Riverbank Terminal maintains procedures that address various modes of process operations such as:

* start-up;

* normal operations;

* temporary operations;

* emergency shutdown;

* normal shutdown; and

* initial startup of a new process. 



These procedures provide guidance for experienced operators and also provide the basis for training new operators. Operating procedures include applicable safety precautions that must be taken in the operation of the facility. The procedures are periodically reviewed and annually certified as current and accurate. The review and certification process involves both operators and technical staff. 



Training:  The Riverbank Terminal facility staff, and Kiva Energy corporate staff, understand that incidents involving the accidental release of regulated substances can be reduced by having trained operations and maintenance staff. A training program, which incorporates specific operating procedures and safe work practices, is an essential element of an effective prevention program. 



The training program is comprised of the following:

* Initial employee training;

* Periodic refresher training (provided at least every three years);

* Training provided as a result of a new equipment addition or modification;

* Competency testing involving written tests and observation following training; and

* Training records for each employee.



Maintenance Procedures & Mechanical Integrity:  The maintenance program at the Riverbank Terminal is intended to preserve the mechanical integrity of the process equipment to minimize the potential for an accidental release. The Riverbank Terminal has established practices and procedures for maintaining process equipm

ion team documents its findings, develops recommendation(s) to prevent a recurrence and forwards these results to the business management team for resolution. 



Employee Participation:  The Facility must rely upon the operational expertise and training of its employees at all levels and disciplines to ensure safe operations. The Facility has implemented procedures regarding employee participation to ensure consideration of their knowledge and experience in all applicable areas of the prevention program.



A formalized employee participation plan for the Riverbank Terminal is being developed with a target completion date of October 31, 2017.

Hot Work Permit:  Regarding hot work that may occur on or near the LPG process, the Riverbank Terminal has developed a written contractor evaluation program and a Hot Work Permit program to document the evaluation of the fire prevention and protection requirements. The Hot Work Permit system is implemented prior to allowing activities that could result the generation of sparks (e.g. cutting and grinding) or that involve the use of open flames. A formalized hot work permit program for the Riverbank Terminal is being developed with a target completion date of October 31, 2017.



Contractor Safety:  The Riverbank Terminal uses contractors during periods of increased maintenance or construction activities. The Kiva Energy evaluates and qualifies contractors who will work on the systems and equipment. Riverbank Terminal has procedures in place to ensure that contractors:

* perform their work in a safe manner;

* have appropriate knowledge and skills;

* are aware of the hazards of their workplace;

* understand what they should do in the event of an emergency;

* understand and follow site specific safety rules; and 

* inform plant personnel of any hazards that they find while performing their work. 



